     1	# Phase 1: Walking Skeleton — CLI Wiring + Parquet/ZIP Foundation - Research
     2	
     3	**Researched:** 2026-06-14
     4	**Domain:** Parquet.Net v5.0.1 low-level nested-schema writing; mzPeak archive format; TRFP CLI wiring
     5	**Confidence:** HIGH (the make-or-break unknown was retired by a compiled spike + round-trip read against the reference reader, not by assumption)
     6	
     7	## Summary
     8	
     9	The single make-or-break unknown — **can Parquet.Net v5.0.1 express mzPeak's nested column
    10	shapes?** — is now **RETIRED with HIGH confidence**. A compiled spike against the actually-installed
    11	`Parquet.Net 5.0.1` (net8.0 lib) wrote a Parquet file containing a nested struct, a list-of-struct
    12	(with empty lists and inner nulls), and two **parallel nullable top-level structs** where each row
    13	populated exactly one and the other was null. pyarrow read it back with the exact intended shapes and
    14	values. ZSTD page compression and string→string KV metadata both work. A minimal STORED-zip archive
    15	(spectra_data + spectra_metadata + mzpeak_index.json) was then built and **opened successfully by the
    16	reference Python reader** (`MzPeakFile`), confirming that Parquet.Net's plain `string`/`list` (32-bit
    17	offset) variants are accepted where the ground truth uses `large_string`/`large_list`.
    18	
    19	Two non-obvious API constraints were discovered and must shape the writer design: (1) columns must be
    20	written **in exact schema leaf order** (`GetDataFields()` order), and (2) when supplying explicit
    21	definition levels, the data array carries **only the defined (non-null) values** as the
    22	non-nullable element type — nulls are conveyed purely through definition levels. The
    23	packed-parallel-null pattern is implemented by giving each parallel top-level struct's leaves a
    24	definition level of 0 on rows where that struct is absent.
    25	
    26	The reference reader's "OPEN" is **not** satisfied by any arbitrary Parquet: the spectrum-metadata
    27	facet requires KV-metadata keys `spectrum_count` and `spectrum_data_point_count` plus a `spectrum`
    28	struct with an `index` leaf; the spectrum-data facet requires a `spectrum_array_index` JSON KV entry.
    29	These minimums are documented below.
    30	
    31	**Primary recommendation:** Use `ParquetWriter.CreateAsync` + `StructField`/`ListField`/`DataField<T>`
    32	schema + `ParquetRowGroupWriter.WriteColumnAsync(DataColumn)` with manual definition/repetition levels;
    33	set `writer.CompressionMethod = CompressionMethod.Zstd` and `writer.CustomMetadata`; emit plain
    34	string/list (no large variants needed); package facets into a STORED `ZipArchive`
    35	(`CompressionLevel.NoCompression`).
    36	
    37	## Architectural Responsibility Map
    38	
    39	| Capability | Primary Tier | Secondary Tier | Rationale |
    40	|------------|-------------|----------------|-----------|
    41	| CLI flag parse / dispatch | TRFP `MainClass`/`RawFileParser` | — | Existing format-routing infrastructure |
    42	| Spectrum data extraction | TRFP `SpectrumWriter` base (`ReadMZData`, `ReadScan`) | — | Already implemented and reused by every writer |
    43	| Parquet schema + column encoding | New `MzPeakSpectrumWriter` + shared Parquet helper | Parquet.Net | Low-level nested encoding the POCO serializer can't do |
    44	| PARAM / CV-column-name helpers | Shared support file | — | Consumed heavily by Phase 3; design now |
    45	| Archive packaging (STORED zip) | New `MzPeakSpectrumWriter` | `System.IO.Compression` | Format-level container, BCL-native |
    46	| KV metadata + array_index JSON | New writer / helper | Newtonsoft.Json (already a dep) | Reader OPEN depends on these keys |
    47	
    48	## Standard Stack
    49	
    50	### Core
    51	| Library | Version | Purpose | Why Standard |
    52	|---------|---------|---------|--------------|
    53	| Parquet.Net | 5.0.1 | Low-level Parquet schema + column writing | Already a TRFP dep [VERIFIED: csproj line 44]; low-level API proven sufficient by spike |
    54	| System.IO.Compression | net8.0 BCL | STORED ZIP container | BCL-native, no new dep |
    55	| Newtonsoft.Json | 13.0.3 | Build `mzpeak_index.json` + KV-metadata JSON | Already a TRFP dep [VERIFIED: csproj line 42] |
    56	
    57	No new NuGet packages are required for Phase 1. **Package Legitimacy Audit is N/A** (no external packages installed).
    58	
    59	### Parquet.Net 5.0.1 verified API surface (reflected from installed DLL)
    60	[VERIFIED: ~/.nuget/packages/parquet.net/5.0.1/lib/net8.0/Parquet.dll]
    61	
    62	```
    63	Parquet.Schema.ParquetSchema(params Field[])            // or IEnumerable<Field>
    64	  DataField[] GetDataFields()                           // leaf fields, IN ORDER
    65	Parquet.Schema.StructField(string name, params Field[] elements)
    66	Parquet.Schema.ListField(string name, Field item)      // item may be a StructField
    67	Parquet.Schema.DataField<T>(string name, bool? nullable = null)
    68	Parquet.Data.DataColumn(DataField field, Array data)                                  // flat, no nulls
    69	Parquet.Data.DataColumn(DataField field, Array definedData, int[] definitionLevels, int[] repetitionLevels)
    70	Parquet.ParquetWriter.CreateAsync(ParquetSchema schema, Stream output, ...) : Task<ParquetWriter>
    71	  ParquetWriter.CompressionMethod { get; set; }         // enum, settable
    72	  ParquetWriter.CustomMetadata    { get; set; }          // IReadOnlyDictionary<string,string>, settable
    73	  ParquetWriter.CreateRowGroup() : ParquetRowGroupWriter
    74	ParquetRowGroupWriter.WriteColumnAsync(DataColumn) : Task
    75	Parquet.CompressionMethod = { None, Snappy, Gzip, Lzo, Brotli, LZ4, Zstd, Lz4Raw }
    76	```
    77	
    78	Note: `Parquet.Serialization.ParquetSerializer` (high-level POCO) still exists but is NOT used here —
    79	it cannot express parallel nullable top-level structs (confirmed by CONTEXT.md decision).
    80	
    81	---
    82	
    83	## Unknown 1 — Parquet.Net nested shapes — DECISION: RESOLVED (the low-level API handles all three)
    84	
    85	**Spike result (compiled + round-tripped):** Parquet.Net 5.0.1 successfully writes and pyarrow reads
    86	back: nested struct, list-of-struct (with empty list + inner null), and parallel nullable top-level
    87	structs (per-row exactly-one-populated). Output below is the literal pyarrow read of the spike file.
    88	
    89	```
    90	spectrum: struct<index: uint64, mz_range: struct<lo,hi>, parameters: list<struct<name:string, val:double>>>
    91	scan:     struct<source_index: uint64, rt: float>
    92	
    93	spectrum row values: [
    94	  {index:10, mz_range:{lo:100.5, hi:2000.0}, parameters:[{name:'a',val:1.5},{name:'b',val:None}]},
    95	  None,                                                  # row1: spectrum NULL
    96	  {index:11, mz_range:{lo:50.0, hi:60.0}, parameters:[]} # row2: empty list
    97	]
    98	scan row values:    [ None, {source_index:10, rt:1.23}, None ]   # only row1 populated
    99	```
   100	
   101	### (a) nested StructField
   102	```csharp
   103	var mzStruct = new StructField("mz_range",
   104	    new DataField<double>("lo"),
   105	    new DataField<double>("hi"));
   106	```
   107	
   108	### (b) ListField whose item is a StructField (list-of-struct)
   109	```csharp
   110	var paramItem = new StructField("item",
   111	    new DataField<string>("name"),
   112	    new DataField<double?>("val"));
   113	var paramsList = new ListField("parameters", paramItem);   // -> list<struct<name,val>>
   114	```
   115	
   116	### (c) parallel nullable top-level structs
   117	```csharp
   118	var spectrum = new StructField("spectrum",
   119	    new DataField<ulong>("index"), mzStruct, paramsList);
   120	var scan = new StructField("scan",
   121	    new DataField<ulong>("source_index"), new DataField<float>("rt"));
   122	var schema = new ParquetSchema(spectrum, scan);   // two parallel top-level structs
   123	```
   124	
   125	### Writing — the two API rules that bite
   126	
   127	**Rule 1 — write columns in schema leaf order.** `GetDataFields()` returns leaves in a fixed order;
   128	`WriteColumnAsync` rejects out-of-order columns (`ArgumentException: cannot write this column,
   129	expected 'integer', passed: 'name'`). Always iterate `GetDataFields()` and write in that order.
   130	
   131	**Rule 2 — defined data + definition levels (NOT nullable arrays).** When you pass explicit
   132	definition levels, the data array must contain only the **present** values, typed as the
   133	non-nullable element type. Passing a `double?[]` with embedded nulls throws
   134	(`expected System.Double[] but passed System.Nullable...`). Express nulls via def levels only.
   135	
   136	**Definition levels are auto-derived from struct nesting.** Parquet.Net makes top-level struct
   137	fields implicitly nullable: a leaf directly under one nullable struct has `MaxDefinitionLevel = 1`
   138	(1 = struct present, 0 = struct null). A leaf under a struct-within-a-struct has `MaxDefinitionLevel = 2`,
   139	and so on. Verified leaf levels for the spike schema:
   140	
   141	```
   142	spectrum/index                         maxDef=1  maxRep=0   (1=spectrum present)
   143	spectrum/mz_range/lo                    maxDef=2  maxRep=0   (2=spectrum+mz_range present)
   144	spectrum/parameters/list/item/name     maxDef=5  maxRep=1   (list-of-struct: def 5 / rep 1)
   145	scan/source_index                      maxDef=1  maxRep=0
   146	```
   147	
   148	**Canonical write loop (the packed-parallel-null pattern):**
   149	```csharp
   150	using var writer = await ParquetWriter.CreateAsync(schema, outStream);
   151	writer.CompressionMethod = CompressionMethod.Zstd;
   152	writer.CustomMetadata = new Dictionary<string,string> {
   153	    ["spectrum_count"] = nSpectra.ToString(),
   154	    ["spectrum_data_point_count"] = "0",                  // metadata facet uses 0
   155	};
   156	using var rg = writer.CreateRowGroup();
   157	
   158	DataField F(string path) =>
   159	    schema.GetDataFields().First(d => d.Path.ToString() == path);  // Path uses '/' separators
   160	
   161	// 3 rows: row0=spectrum, row1=scan, row2=spectrum(empty params)
   162	// spectrum.index present on rows 0,2 (def=1), absent on row1 (def=0):
   163	await rg.WriteColumnAsync(new DataColumn(F("spectrum/index"),
   164	    new ulong[]{10, 11}, new int[]{1,0,1}, null));         // rep=null for non-repeated leaves
   165	await rg.WriteColumnAsync(new DataColumn(F("spectrum/mz_range/lo"),
   166	    new double[]{100.5, 50.0}, new int[]{2,0,2}, null));
   167	// list-of-struct leaf: 2 items in row0, struct absent row1 (def0), empty list row2 (def2):
   168	await rg.WriteColumnAsync(new DataColumn(F("spectrum/parameters/list/item/name"),
   169	    new string[]{"a","b"}, new int[]{5,5,0,2}, new int[]{0,1,0,0}));
   170	await rg.WriteColumnAsync(new DataColumn(F("spectrum/parameters/list/item/val"),
   171	    new double[]{1.5}, new int[]{5,4,0,2}, new int[]{0,1,0,0}));  // val null at row0/item1 = def4
   172	// scan struct present only on row1:
   173	await rg.WriteColumnAsync(new DataColumn(F("scan/source_index"),
   174	    new ulong[]{10}, new int[]{0,1,0}, null));
   175	```
   176	
   177	**Definition-level cheat sheet for list-of-struct (`parameters` under a nullable struct):**
   178	- `0` = parent struct null (no list)
   179	- `2` = struct present, list present but empty (one entry per row, rep=0)
   180	- `5` = item present, leaf value non-null
   181	- `4` = item present, leaf value null (e.g. nullable `val`/`accession`/`unit`)
   182	
   183	**Fallback (not needed):** none. The low-level API expresses every required shape. No
   184	manual Arrow IPC or external tooling is required.
   185	
   186	---
   187	
   188	## Unknown 2 — Compression + Arrow large variants — DECISION: ZSTD via enum; plain string/list, large NOT required
   189	
   190	**ZSTD:** [VERIFIED: spike round-trip] `Parquet.CompressionMethod.Zstd` exists and works.
   191	Set `writer.CompressionMethod = CompressionMethod.Zstd;` before creating the row group. pyarrow
   192	reported every column compression as `ZSTD` in the spike output. This matches the ground-truth files,
   193	whose every column is ZSTD [VERIFIED: pyarrow inspection of small.unpacked.mzpeak].
   194	
   195	**Large variants:** [VERIFIED: spike inspection] Parquet.Net 5.0.1 emits **plain `string` and `list`
   196	(32-bit offsets)** — it does NOT emit Arrow `large_string`/`large_list`. There is no API option in the
   197	low-level path to force the large variants.
   198	
   199	**Are large variants mandatory?** **No.** [VERIFIED: reference reader OPEN] A minimal archive whose
   200	metadata facet used plain `string` (`id`) and plain `list` (`parameters`) was opened by the reference
   201	Python reader and the `spectrum` table parsed correctly (`id='index=0'`, `parameters=[]`). The reader
   202	uses pyarrow which transparently accepts both 32-bit and 64-bit offset variants. **Decision: emit
   203	whatever Parquet.Net produces (plain string/list); do not attempt to force large variants.**
   204	
   205	> Caveat (LOW risk): plain `string`/`list` use 32-bit offsets, capping a single column chunk's
   206	> cumulative string/list bytes at 2 GiB. For TRFP per-RAW outputs this is not a practical limit, and
   207	> row-group chunking keeps each chunk small. Note for Phase 3/4 if extremely large metadata columns
   208	> ever appear (they won't for spectra metadata).
   209	
   210	---
